<refnamediv id='purpose'>
<refname>gimplut</refname>
<refpurpose>
  convert GIMP gradient (ggr) files to binary lookup tables (lut).
</refpurpose>
</refnamediv>

<refsynopsisdiv id='synopsis'>
<cmdsynopsis>
  <command>gimplut</command>    
    <arg choice='opt'>-h </arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-o <replaceable>file</replaceable></arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-s <replaceable>samples</replaceable></arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-v </arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-V </arg>
    <arg choice='opt'><replaceable>file</replaceable></arg>
</cmdsynopsis>
</refsynopsisdiv>

<refsect1 id='description'><title>DESCRIPTION</title>
<para>
  The <command>gimplut</command> utility converts gradient files 
  from the 
  <citerefentry>
    <refentrytitle>GIMP</refentrytitle>
    <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
  </citerefentry>,
  the GNU Image Manipulation Program, to a binary lookup table 
  format commonly used by medical imaging software; in 
  particular the 
  <citerefentry>
    <refentrytitle>Medcon</refentrytitle>
    <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
  </citerefentry>
  package.
</para>

<para>
  The LUT format consists of 
  <option>n</option> red, 
  <option>n</option> green and 
  <option>n</option> blue bytes, 
  interpreted as integers from 0 to 255.
</para>

<para>
  The program will read from 
  <filename moreinfo="refentry" path="/dev">stdin</filename> 
  if a file is not specified as the final argument, and write to 
  <filename moreinfo="refentry" path="/dev">stdout</filename> 
  if the <option>-o</option> option is not specified.
</para>

</refsect1>

<refsect1 id='options'><title>OPTIONS</title>
<variablelist remap='TP'>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-h</option>, <option>--help</option>
  </term>
  <listitem>
    <para>Brief help.</para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-o</option>, <option>--output</option>
  <replaceable>file</replaceable>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>Write the output to  <replaceable>file</replaceable>, 
  rather than 
  <filename moreinfo="refentry" path="/dev">stdout</filename>.
  </para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-s</option>, <option>--samples</option>
  <replaceable>number</replaceable>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>
    Use the specified  <replaceable>number</replaceable>
    of samples rather than 256.
  </para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-v</option>, <option>--verbose</option>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>Verbose operation.</para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-V</option>, <option>--version</option>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>Version information.</para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

</variablelist>
</refsect1>

<refsect1 id='files'><title>FILES</title>

<para>
  The <command>gimplut</command> program will search for 
  gradient files 
</para>

<itemizedlist mark="dash">

  <listitem>
    <para>
      in the directories specified in <envar>GIMP_GRADIENTS</envar>;
    </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
    <para>
      in the user's GIMP directory,
      <envar
	  >HOME</envar><filename class="directory"
	  >/.gimp-<replaceable
	  >version</replaceable>/gradients</filename>;
    </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
    <para>	
      in the standard locations
      <filename class="directory"
		>/usr/share/gimp/<replaceable
		>version</replaceable>/gradients</filename>
      and 
      <filename class="directory"
		>/usr/share/local/gimp/<replaceable
		>version</replaceable>/gradients</filename>,
    </para>
  </listitem>

</itemizedlist>
  
<para>
  where <replaceable>version</replaceable> ranges over 
  feasible version numbers.
</para>

</refsect1>

<refsect1 id='environment'><title>ENVIRONMENT</title>
<para>
  If the <envar>GIMP_GRADIENTS</envar> variable is defined then
  each colon-separated directory therein will be searched for
  gradient files.
</para>
</refsect1>

<refsect1 id='caveats'><title>CAVEATS</title>

<para>
  The alpha channel of the input is completely ignored
  in the output.
</para>

<para>
  At some point in the future the functionality of this
  program will be transferred to the 
  <citerefentry>
    <refentrytitle>svgx</refentrytitle>
    <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
  </citerefentry>
  program.
</para>

</refsect1>

